### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

The way httpResource's reactivity is implemented can lead to unintentional reloads.

For example:

```ts
interface Product {
  id: number;
  hasData: boolean;
  description: string;
}

@Component({
  imports: [ChildComponent, FormsModule],
  template: `
    <div>
      <label>Description</label>
      <input type="text" [(ngModel)]="description">
    </div>
    <app-child-component [product]="product()">
  `
})
class HostComponent {
  product = signal<Product>({id: 1, hasData: true, description: ''});
  description = linkedSignal(() => this.product().description);
  constructor() {
    effect(() => {
      const description = this.description();
      const product = untracked(this.product);
      if (product.description !== description) {
        this.product.set({...product, description});
      }
    });
  }
}

@Component({ selector: 'app-child-component' })
class ChildComponent {
  product = input.required<Product>();
  productData = httpResource(() => `/api/product-data/${this.product().id}`);
}
```

For every letter typed in the HostComponent, the child component's httpResource will fire a new HTTP Request, even though the resource requested is the exact same every single time.

This is because currently httpResource reloads whenever any signal value used inside of the urlFn is updated.


### Proposed solution

I think the urlFn should automatically be converted into a computed, such that the resource is only reloaded when the requested URL changes (or when httpResource.reload() is called).

### Alternatives considered

Developers can add their own `computed` to resolve this issue. I personally don't think that is ideal. Before posting this issue I asked a few people what they thought would happen in the case above / similar cases, most did not expect the resource to reload.

The above example is very obvious, but in real codebases these are almost certainly further apart. I don't think there's any particularly strong reason not to convert the url into a computed by default (or heck, if that's too much overhead somehow, the resolved url could be stored on the HttpResourceRef and new values can be checked against the previous)

### Command

